Parliament does not support the amendment giving freedom to Tymoshenko
Today, the Parliament of Ukraine, in amending the Code of Criminal Procedure, rejected an attempt to repeal an article that condemned the leader of the opposition, Yulia Tymoshenko.
An amendment that would have led to the release of the former Prime Minister in prison was rejected during the second reading of the draft law on the commutation of sentences for economic offences.
In October, Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison for signing a gas deal with Russia, which was deemed to be a disadvantage.
The sentence is not yet final; the court will hear Tymoshenko's appeal in December.
Tymoshenko claims that the sentence is a political revenge of the regime; in the West, the trial was also suspected of bias.
The proposal to repeal article 365 of the Code of Criminal Procedure, under which the former Prime Minister had been convicted, had been supported by 147 members of Parliament.
Ratification would require 226 votes.
