Nutrition of Obese Children: No breakfast and no sausage for dinner
More than one third of children between the ages of 9 and 13 weigh more than the norm; while 9 per cent of schoolchildren are overweight, 5 per cent suffer from obesity.
According to a recent study, children suffering from obesity usually come from unhealthy families.
Once again, we see the importance of the environment and behaviour that accompany human beings to their healthy development.
For example, sausage appears almost twice as often on the tables of children suffering from obesity as in families with children of normal weight.
More than 19% of children suffering from obesity ate French potatoes for dinner on the eve of an educational event called Obesity was no accident.
Moreover, families of children suffering from obesity do not engage in sports, but this is true for most families of modern schoolchildren - only 15 per cent of the children said that their parents find time to exercise at least once a week.
The study was conducted among 900 children.
The study was carried out at the end of last school year, involving almost 900 primary-school students throughout Bohemia.
Obesity was not an accident for the second consecutive year, with the support of the insurance company Všeobecná zdravotní pojiávna and Unilever.
To date, more than 12,000 pupils in grades 4 to 8 have joined the project.
Adequate nutrition and adequate exercise are the main determinants of the rapidly growing number of children suffering from either overweight or obesity.
"For example, only half of those interviewed said that they eat five meals a day, according to the breakfast-dinner-dinner-dinner scheme, which is one of the prerequisites for proper nutrition," says one of the conclusions of the study.
No lunch or sausage in the evenings.
Experts warn that even relative details, such as the constant time of family breakfast, are important for healthy development.
In the Czech Republic, only 23% of school-age families have breakfast together.
In most families, everyone eats breakfast separately.
The worst discovery is that people don't eat breakfast at all in every tenth family.
And yet breakfast is the basis of the right daily diet.
The study found that fried food is more commonly used in families with children suffering from obesity.
Almost everyone, regardless of weight, drinks sweet cool drinks every day (70%).
Although more than 40 per cent of children regularly participate in sports, this figure falls by more than half, to 15 per cent, when it comes to their parents.
Make your own menu.
In another part of the study, selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) were asked to draw up their own menu based on the products offered and based on their tastes and preferences.
"The food preferences of Czech children between the ages of 12 and 15 are far from the ideal of healthy nutrition."
Their favorite food includes a large amount of flour, meat, and sweet food.
"A particular concern is the high popularity of sweet cool drinks," says the final part of the study.
As the main luncheon, the pasta defeated the bird with a small margin.
However, children showed little interest in bean, fish and vegetable dishes.
Desiring a Healthy Lifestyle
The study also showed that children were willing to change their eating habits, provided that they were provided with relevant information.
“Many participants in the review team have shown a significant shift in preferences towards healthy food when completing a questionnaire after the lecture, Obesity is not an accident”, says the project's outcome.
This was particularly evident, for example, in the case of sweet, cool drinks, with more children preferring just water to them.
In addition, as a main dish, children have more frequented birds and fish, limiting the amount of sweet food and pastries.
