V Need for Speed: Escape occurs in America.
Overview
What was supposed to be a carefree walk turned into a routine morning trip to work because of a series of completely inappropriate and careless mistakes.
The ambition was somewhat satisfied, but it doesn't matter, because nobody really wanted to do the extra work.
Before the release of the new version with the subheading "Escape", there were great hopes.
It was expected to move the previous series of "Need For Speed" in a new direction; the demos showed that the game would take its rightful place in the racing genre.
We were curious to see the parts of the game where the main character gets out of the car and runs.
As is often the case with NFS, in the end, much is different from what we expected.
The game is a pretty good arcade race, but the general impression is that it's ruined a few unnecessary mistakes that have been in this series for several years.
So, in reality, it's not a mistake, it's an unexplained laziness of the developers.
Adventure starts very well.
You become part of a story whose main hero, Jack, decides to solve some personal problems by participating in an illegal race through America.
You get in a car on the west coast, in San Francisco, and your job is to get to New York first.
This idea has some interesting features.
The route consists of ten stages divided into more than fifty races.
This means that each race follows its own route, and the individual stages take place in a diverse and interesting environment.
So it doesn't feel like the same thing happens in the game all the time.
Although the graphs are at the same level as in previous parts of the series, it is nice to see some of the tracks.
Yet, the game does not give rise to strong emotions.
Although driving through the desert, in the autumn suburbs, or high in the snowy mountains is a pleasure.
In addition, the race occasionally revives an unusual detail.
In the desert, for example, you are caught in a sandstorm that significantly reduces visibility.
On the other hand, the mountains need to be careful not to fall under the avalanche.
The individual races are quite well organized.
There are only a few varieties, but that's enough.
For a while you've been trying to outrun a few rivals (mostly a normal race); then you're trying to improve time (standard race with a stopwatch); or you're competing with one opponent.
Among other things, you run into the police from time to time, which makes your task even more difficult.
The components outside the car are new.
It's just an interactive animation where most of the time Jack runs away from someone and you have to help him by pressing the right buttons at the right time.
It's not complicated.
Although it is surprising that these fragments are much smaller than you might expect (only three to be accurate).
In fact, it turns out that it's good for a game because it's not boring; given all the above, it's one of the things that makes the game more interesting.
The racing model is following the tracks of the previous models.
This means that it is no longer a special thing, but it is not a shortcoming.
If you're looking for a fake real life, you're going to have to look elsewhere.
Still, this driving model is very suitable for dynamic races, although better options can be found in the market.
So far, so good.
After a while, however, problems begin.
Unlike the driving model, the collision model is not as good.
You don't expect complex transformations and collisions from this game, but if you have no idea what your machine will do before you hit an object, something's wrong.
Usually, overtaking or passing cars in a dense stream, you sometimes touch another car slightly, and yet sometimes in a very similar situation, your car starts to spin wildly.
Or she's broken up.
It's not important because of the restart system, but it's enough to ruin the fun.
Re-starts are designed so that if you crash or go far off the track, the game brings you back to the point where it stopped.
However, only five restarts are available for each race.
If you use them all, you'll have to start the race from the start.
It's helpful if something doesn't work, but you can't rely entirely on it.
Sometimes restarts aren't enough, and you have to memorize a particular part of the race.
An important shortcoming of the game is the fact that the same things often happen in the same places.
For example, some turns have to be done in a certain way, or you just won't fit in.
In other cases, you meet civilian vehicles at a certain location in the same configuration, whether you arrive first, fifth, five seconds early, or a minute later.
It's particularly annoying when you see your opponent travel easily between two cars moving in the opposite direction, whereas when you get there, the machines are already positioned so that you need either to bypass them or to slow down.
It doesn't matter when you're around them; it's all made up that things always happen right in front of you.
There are other advantages to rivals.
During the game, you find several places where, regardless of the time, the same rival overtakes you in the same place.
It's especially obvious at the end of the game, on a long bridge where you're driving in the opposite direction.
Obviously, your opponent must stand before you no matter what.
The thing is, when he's driving in front of you, he's making things worse for you, leading to one or more accidents at this site.
You can understand the attempt to make the game more interesting and filled with adrenaline, but it's so obvious that it's starting to get irritated quickly.
It's a shame, because despite a simple driving pattern, the game is interesting and sometimes so eventful that you don't have time to pay attention to what's going on around you.
It doesn't matter what keeps you from being bored-- a concept with 50 unique tracks, a series of races, or something.
The idea of changing cars during races is unusual.
You need to keep track of the gas stations on the way, because that's what your car can switch to, despite the fact that in most cases the one you already have is enough.
Cars are divided into three categories.
Sports cars are suitable for cities; powerful American cars are for straight sections of the highway; and exotic supersports are for technical driving, such as curved mountain lanes.
The main mode of history mode is closely linked to the mode of challenge mode; it is a race on individual plots that you will learn as you go along.
Here you win both medals and points for your personal affairs that are common to the challenges and Story regimes.
Many facilities are available for higher levels of driving, ranging from cars to profile data.
In addition, the profile is linked to the online function of Autolog, which, among other things, compares your performance with that of other players, and provides communication to the public.
This is another weakness that is difficult to understand; it is an example from the last race in sequence.
You and your car get into a subway tunnel (let's say so) where you're on the tracks in the dark (let's say so).
Your speedometer shows the figures from 150 to 200 km/h, when suddenly a subway train hits you from behind, turning your car into a pile of scrap metal.
For a few days, our editorials have been discussing whether no one really thought for a second at the time of the game's creation, or whether its creators really think we're such morons.
The technical component of the game is nothing special; but the overall impression from the video series is mostly pleasant, sometimes even amazing.
Although it is unfortunate that at some critical moments the quality of the recording, sometimes quite strongly, is declining.
This is particularly true of incidents involving a large number of participants, where a good recording would not help you very much, either.
Sound's fine; soundtrack's on the amateur.
In order to please the widest possible audience of young people, the soundtrack's songs from different styles have entered; but it is unlikely that many people will buy the game because of its music.
The general impression of Ned for Speed: The escape is rather disorderly.
If the game had avoided unnecessary mistakes, we could honestly say that Escape is the best part of NFS in the last few years.
Anyway, the game leaves a sense of unfinished business.
Of course, it's a good sport, but prepare yourself for failings to blind you as a searchlight for the airport.
