The brand story:
IBM's innovator is entering the second century of his existence.
If anyone wants to find a word that best expresses IMB's strategy, the closest is likely to be "long-lasting."
For the general public, IBM is a symbol of the technological revolution; the company is considered to be very modern, although it was founded over a century ago.
The company's long-term viability was laid down by its first boss, the dreamer Thomas J. Watson, Sr.
He believed in his motto that many of the world's problems could be solved easily if people wanted to think.
His slogan "Think!" thus became the stamp around which the life of the future giant unfolded (as well as the name of his internal magazine, which IMB began to publish in 1935).
Moreover, it was the foundation of the corporate culture that Watson carefully built.
"For us in IBM, long-term thinking means a constant movement towards the future.
