History of IBM: From cheese knife to space missions.
==History==IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York a century ago, and its original name, "Compilation, Tabulation, Recording Corporation", was rather complicated.
It was named IBM in 1924, originally called the brand used for the company's branches in Canada and South America.
The foundation of the future IBM was the merger of four companies, whose history began in the 1880s.
They had technology, such as a legendary “task watch”, i.e. a clock that records the time when employees come and go.
The architect of the new company was a businessman, Charles Ranlet Flint, who also headed the company's board of trustees until 1930.
Flint hired Thomas J. Watson, director of a rival company, to help him run the company.
The leader then cast the founder of IBM into the shadow - Watson's ideas remain the foundation of an unshakeable corporate culture and identity.
Watson was in charge of the company until 1952.
IBM, as is clear from the name, began with the production and sale of various business equipment, ranging from cheese knives and meat cutters to cash machines.
In the first four years of Watson’s leadership, the revenue doubled to $9 million, and the company’s expansion to all continents began.
Watson became so important to the company that after almost 40 years, his son, Thomas Watson Jr., took his place in the director's chair.
Under his leadership, IBM began to develop artificial intelligence technologies and created the first programming language.
In the 1960s, both IBM staff and computers helped NASA control space flights to Mercury, Saturn, and in 1969, a man's flight to the moon.
Meanwhile, in 1964, IBM developed the first family of computers, the IBM line System/360.
The classic PC, which defined computer standards at the time, called IBM 5150, was introduced into the market in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold the Chinese company Lenovo’s computer production, simultaneously buying the PricewaterhouseCoopers consulting office, thus focusing entirely on consulting and high-value-added services.
Over the past three years, IBM has made great strides with its concept of the Smart Planet.
Its purpose is to make reasonable use of technologies in areas that have not yet been planned and to improve the road situation and urban governance.
In the area of commerce, IBM recently introduced the Smart Commerce platform, which helps businessmen control the entire trading cycle.
The IBM tradition is strong even in our country.
In the former Czechoslovakia, as the first country to be located simultaneously in central and eastern Europe, IBM founded its branch office in 1932.
Today, IBM CZ also manages a strategic outsourcing centre in Brno.
The headquarters of central and eastern Europe is located in Prague, where there is also a world-level research group on speech recognition.
