Trends in travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, only five government travel agencies were able to work in the former Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Because travel to the West was severely restricted, travel agencies at that time mostly sold tours to socialist bloc countries.
Thus, Czech tourists travelled on vacation to the German Democratic Republic; the Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea on the Black Sea); Bulgaria; Romania (both countries on the Black Sea); and Hungary (Balaton).
The only exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when we had the opportunity to travel to Yugoslavia, and then the Yugoslav regime turned to the West, causing considerable restrictions on Czech tourists to travel to Yugoslavia.
The great paradox of the socialist period was that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. Czechoslovakia) were not allowed to travel individually in socialist countries.
If a Czechoslovak citizen wanted to go on his own, for example, to the Soviet Union or Poland, an invitation letter from that country was needed; otherwise, an individual journey was impossible.
At the time, travel agencies offered to travel to the West, but it was either to stand in line all night with a sleeping bag or to have "good friends" at the agency.
And that wasn't all.
The currency permit was needed for travel to the West, and it was not given to politically unreliable people who were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not freely convertible; it was impossible to obtain money (Western currency) for travel to the West without a currency permit.
The Czechs most often spent their vacations at home, resulting in large numbers of cottages and summer houses, a habit that continues to this day.
After 1989, tourism in the Czech Republic thus survived a real revolution.
While before 1989 leave in the GDR or Bulgaria was the culmination of our travels, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million vacations in countries around the world.
The great paradox, which we no longer understand, is that until 1989 we were not free to visit Croatia, which was currently the most popular, because it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
In early 1990, the need to obtain a visa to neighbouring countries in Western Europe was abolished, triggering a huge wave of short trips, mainly to Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks couldn't get enough travel to the West, so everyone wanted to go there for a moment.
For example, in Paris, Czech tourists slept in tented parks because their income at the time was insufficient for a hotel or board.
A typical feature of Czech tourism at that time was the desire to bring in their own food (conservatives, salami, etc.) to save money.
Another important point is the introduction of a freely convertible Czech kroner, and after decades, our tourists are finally free to buy Western currency.
Our standard of living and average income have been rising, leading to another important development around 1997.
Since 1997, increased demand has allowed travel agencies to prepare regular charter flights; compared to the past, air travel has become extremely cheap because of the ability to book wholesale discounts.
By the late 1990s, the Czechs did not need a visa to visit virtually every developed world other than the United States, which made our travels even easier.
The next significant event in the history of travel after the revolution took place in 2000, with strong demand leading historically to the first direct charter flight from the Czech Republic to an exotic country, Thailand.
Since then, direct charter flights have taken Czech tourists to warm exotic countries, and this winter flights from the Czech Republic will take twelve exotic directions.
Currently, about 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
Another important event of this period, which symbolizes our development after the revolution, took place in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the United States abolished the need to obtain a visa for Czech tourists, thus permanently joining the world's most developed countries.
For the first time in history in 2008, the Czechs spent more than half of their leave abroad (50.3%); and for the first time in history, they spent more than 15,000 kroner per person during their leave abroad, including their destination expenses.
