Peter Englund's strained and very kind new book, Beauty and Grief: The Personal History of World War I, begins with a long list of actors from which the heart freezes.
Here's the advice to read next: carefully cut out this page and use it as a bookmark.
You will meet these people very closely as Mr. Englund tells you, and this list of actors will be your GPS, your beacon, at times when, like one of these men and women, you'll get lost in the fog of war.
Mr. Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new Permanent Secretary of the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize in Literature.
The book he's written now is unusual, he describes it quite accurately as "work on anti-history."
There are few known names, important treaties or famous battles; there are almost no ambassadors, clever journalists, or discussions on tactics and military equipment.
It's not so much a book about what was, he explains, as a book about what it was like, it's about feelings, impressions, experiences and state of mind.
The book "Beauty and Grief" combined the experiences of 20 more or less insignificant men and women in the war years, from both sides of the front line, from schoolgirls and nerd scientists to climbers, doctors, ambulance drivers and employees.
Some of these people will be heroes.
Someone gets captured, loses an arm or a leg, goes crazy or dies.
Their lives are glimmering here like church candles: new ones are added to a host of others, and some are extinguished at that time.
Mr. Englund's book is a departure from the standard of historical books.
This is an amendment to the notion that the First World War was only a severe trenches war on the Western Front.
Beauty and Grief has been able to provide a panorama of other theatres of war: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
The soldiers in this book are hit by bee hives; one of them meets Christmas in Egypt under the pyramids; the unresolved problem is tsetse flies.
It's an exciting book, almost from the beginning.
War covers the lives of these people like a natural disaster, like Hurricane Katrina smelling like smokeless powder.
When a canon is heard, and you're a woman at home with children, will you stay where you are or will you run away?
Anyway, who's coming?
Almost no one understands what's going on or why we have to fight this war.
“The lack of facts,” Mr. Englund notes, “resurrected by guesses, assumptions, hopes, fears, obsessive ideas, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and rumors”.
"Beauty and Grief" tracks the fate of people like Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, and Richard Stumpf, a young marine of the German high seas fleet.
Their stories are mainly taken from memoirs, letters and other materials already published.
The stories about their lives may be scary or exciting, but they are highly alive, thanks to the small moments and fragmentary details collected by Mr. Englund.
Many of them are about deprivation and how to deal with it.
Telling the story of a German schoolgirl, he says, "Erzac, everywhere Erzac."
"Replacement, fake aluminum, fake rubber, paper bandages, wooden buttons."
He keeps talking about erzaz food in Germany.
He describes “dressed rice meat welded in ovine fat (and decorated with a fake bone made of wood); tobacco made of dried roots and dried potato skin; shoes beaten with wood”.
He notes that there were “837 registered substitutes for meat permitted in sausage production, 511 registered substitutes for coffee”.
Some stories speak of honour and courage.
One American notes the very desire for cruelty and says about war: "You feel that, after all, it's what men were made for, not to sit in comfortable chairs with cigarettes and whiskey, an evening paper or a bestseller, and to say that this display is civilization, and under your decorated shirt with cufflinks, there's no barbarian hiding."
On the contrary, a British soldier notes that he is likely to die and that no one will notice or grieve.
“When a person humbles himself to the idea of self-sacrifice, he would like to think it would happen in front of the public,” he writes.
But it's the other way around, it's like a "sentenced man hanged in secret."
Other comments concern old Europe, which is falling apart, and new types of fear.
"Conflict has become an increasingly economic competition," wrote Mr. Englund, "war factories."
He notes the coming of someone called "a new view in the beginning of the century: a beautifully expressed and ideologically convinced mass murderer in a well-sewn suit that organizes the carnage sitting at a written table."
People act unexpectedly: lowly acts are as much heroic as heroism.
Mr. Englund spoke about soldiers who tried their best to get sexually transmitted diseases from prostitutes to avoid serving on the front.
“The most grotesque expression of this can be seen in the trade in gonorrhea, which the soldiers bought and smeared on their genitals in the hope of going to the hospital,” he writes.
"All desperate people rubbed him in the eye, which often led to lifelong blindness."
The prose of Mr. Englund, translated with the Swedish Peter Graves, is flexible, but unscrupulous, well suited to his humanistic task.
In dozens of small scenes, he shows how the war “liberated completely uncontrollable forces: extreme nationalism, social revolution, religious hatred”.
