The walls have eyes: How researchers study you on Facebook
Before becoming a new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, Anders Bering Breivik was just a regular guy who said his anti-immigration views on the Internet.
On Monday, Breivik, who confessed to the Norwegian massacre in July, which claimed the lives of 77 people, appeared at his first public hearing.
Although Braewick could act alone, he was far from alone online: he spent a lot of time preparing to attack his computer, interacting with millions of nationalists who support right-wing groups on social media.
After the summer tragedy, researchers wanted to learn more about these people.
But how do we find them?
Easy, we just have to go to Facebook.
"We realized it was easy to get close to them," says Jamie Bartlett, the lead author of a recent report on European cyber-populism at the British DEMOS Research Center.
The personal data stock on Facebook is so large, says Bartlett, that researchers could easily use the website's promotional tool to single out the necessary demographic group with scientific accuracy, which is what marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett's team found half a million right-wing fans all over Europe and then pitched them ads, but instead of showing a new group or a diet product, the ad offered the user a survey that asked about their level of education, attitudes to violence, and optimism about their own future.
With the help of Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview more than 10,000 participants in 14 extreme right-wing parties in 11 European countries - even without leaving the office.
"This is a completely new way to do research," Bartlett says.
Some of the results are less striking: right-wing onlineists are more likely to be male youths who are dissatisfied with immigration.
But suddenly, "those who combine their online activity with offline activity are more intelligent, more democratic and less aggressive than those who just hide behind the monitor."
The work of DEMOS is just one example of how Facebook becomes a new popular tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centres, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study everything in the world, from health issues to social trends expressed in the Lights, posts on the wall and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three entries a day, Facebook’s “super-relevant information” triggers a research boom, increasing the number of scientific articles with the title of the site by 800 per cent over the past five years.
For some researchers, Facebook’s beauty is that it provides an opportunity to study people who cannot be approached on the street with a notebook.
"Once upon a time, if you wanted to interview people from the British National Party, it would be very difficult to identify them."
"You would have to join the party, and they would never have accepted you," Bartlett says.
"Facebook eliminates all this-- you're talking to them directly."
Others say that the site could identify and investigate problems of social health.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues showed that students who discussed their drunken performances on Facebook were much more at risk of alcoholism than students who were silent about it.
Moreno suggests that students’ peers, such as their hostels, could monitor the site and intervene to help a student who too often updates drunk status.
"You can't solve the problem without finding it," said Washington Post Dimitri Christis, co-author Moreno and director of the Center for Child Health, Behaviour and Development at Seattle Children's Research Institute.
"We have found a way to identify children at risk who would not otherwise have been found."
Facebook also continuously extracts different kinds of data about its users.
The website's data processing team processed statistics on relationship status and Valentine's Day, the voter turnout in mid-2010, and the National Happiness Index (mostly using information only available to them - cyberfreedom champions have long insisted that the site should make its extensive data collection publicly available for research).
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not - in exchange for playing Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away, the site can process your personal data.
But what about when Facebook users become part of a study they don't even know about?
While researchers have well-defined standards for offline research, online data are publicly available.
"I don't think many users have even thought about what a researcher can look at their profiles," says Neil Selwin, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Laboratory, about a study he conducted in 2006 using the public Facebook pages of students.
"As far as they knew, it was just between them and their friends."
The question then arises of methodology.
There's no guarantee even offline that the subject of the study is completely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know how much information in the profile and on the user page is true.
"What you're saying on Facebook and what you're doing outside Facebook are two completely different things," Selvin says.
That is why, despite its years of technological research, Selwin thinks that the notebook and pen are still the best research tools that can be used.
"Nothing can replace going out into the real world and communicating with real people," he says.
"It is assumed that social research is about social research, and most social research is still offline."
