“What we see now is an increase in unemployment, which involves several factors, including a loss of liquidity in the market to limit the resources imposed by the law that was passed in Congress to combat money-laundering, because people who illegally own dollars have difficulty working with them, investing and using them in something,” he said.
Stopped immigration
Lopez Cervantes said that there is also a demographic factor in the rise in unemployment.
“The number of people who leave the state to seek employment abroad has been limited in the US, primarily because of entry difficulties, and the second because once they enter, they already face a lot of difficulties in finding work, so a group of people stay and demand jobs here in the state, as a result of which unemployment is rising”, he said.
Violation of formal requirements
The analysis of the labour market in Sinaloa is getting worse if you look at the large number of violations that prevail in working conditions, according to INEGI, 60.38 per cent of the active population of the State is working without being mentioned as workers in any social protection institution.
In addition to unemployment and irregular formalities, another reminder of employment in the State is given by low wages; in the State, the lowest wages in the country are recorded by the Mexican Social Security Institute and the Ministry of Labour and Social Welfare.
The average monthly income of Sinaloa workers was 5.352 pesos until September, well below the national average of 7.375 pesos.
Reducing FDI
In addition to the decline in economic activity and high unemployment rates, 2011 saw the largest outflow of foreign direct investment in the past 10 years, according to the Ministry of Finance, between January and July, state FDI amounted to $630,697. This represents a decline of 87.74 per cent, compared with $5,143.312 during the same period last year.
For its part, the Ministry of Economic Development of the State Government recorded only 17.280,000 pesos of investment during the year, mainly from service companies.
Debt
Against the backdrop of the economic downturn, in July, the state government requested the approval of a 3 billion pesos loan during the state congress, which would be used to invest in infrastructure projects in 18 municipalities to revive the economy, only 2,600 million pesos were approved at the local level, and until November no debt advantage was expected in any sector of the state economy.
Reactions
For business representatives, the first year of the government's Mario López Valdés demonstrates a lack of government capacity.
Miguel Loredo López, President of the National Chamber of Manufacturing, said that during 2011 there was a lack of harmonization among the various sectors, including the state government itself.
“The efficiency of the economy in Sinaloa this year has been really low, has to work hard to recover the positions lost this year, in 2012 we have to redouble our efforts, we have not been able to agree on the efforts of all and, above all, the good and synchronized work of the new government team, we hope that next year will be much better,” he said.
Economic slowdown
Lopez Loredo said that events such as the early freezes this year stopped the state economy and its efficiency and growth were limited.
“The low size of the economy is the result of several events, including frost, one of the main effects was the slow economy, which is not fast enough to create economic dynamics that allow for an acceptable level of processes, goods and services, and therefore, at the end of the year, we close it below our expectations”, he said.
Revision of the direction
Theodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Confederation of Employers of the Mexican Republic in Sinaloa, said that the state needed to continue its most dynamic production activity.
“In general, we found that we were working on it, we believe that there is a need to develop a long-term programme that redefines the direction and economic direction of the state, and we need to mobilize all the material and human resources Sinaloa has,” he said.
Work to be undertaken
President Coparmex stressed the importance of determining the future direction in order to better guide the Government's efforts.
“In general, I would say that the Government is trying to be successful in various areas, there has been little progress in terms of economic development, but it is important to develop a long-term programme,” he said.
He noted that the current administration had demonstrated progress in its own way of conducting public policy.
“There are facts that allow us to say that the government is beginning to get involved, and that I can say that some work has been done, and I think the government realizes that much more needs to be done,” he said.
