The Court will confirm the “digital television transition” in Mexico in 2015
The replacement of analogue signals with digital ones is one of the most important changes the world has experienced in recent years.
The Supreme Court of Justice (SC) rejected the constitutional claims made by the Senate and the House of Representatives against the presidential decree, which transfers the so-called “digital television transition” from 2021 to 2015, as there were no eight votes required to cancel it.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Mesa, considered that President Felipe Calderón had not exceeded his mandate by issuing a decree detailing the actions to move to digital terrestrial television.
As a result, constitutional claims filed by the Senate were dismissed because of the lack of a qualified majority of eight votes required for the court to rule on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree and it remains in force.
The draft statement prepared by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero proposed that the decree be declared unconstitutional because the regulation of the radio and television programme was a right established by law for the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in violation of the principles of hierarchical subordination and legislative reserve.
Only Salvidar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sanchez Cordero voted in favour of the project.
On this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies held two constitutional debates to challenge the decree and support the complaints, and Minister Sánchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all the actions mentioned therein concerning the introduction of digital broadcasting.
At the ministerial meeting, it was also decided to reject the request of the Chamber of Deputies without entering into a discussion of the draft, also under the responsibility of Minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the Prime Minister said that he disagreed with the arguments of the draft in the sense that the federal executive branch could not determine the general rules for the measures to be prepared by the public administration.
“I also do not believe that if this were to happen, it would affect the regulatory authority's autonomy”, and recalled that planning public policy in strategic areas such as telecommunications has to do with the federal executive, which has a constitutional mandate, the administration of the State.
The replacement of analogue signals with digital ones - one of the most important changes that have taken place in recent years - has led to better use of the radio-electric spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
Postponing the transition, he said, would mean postponing the benefits of conversion into a digital form, which includes meeting public needs, which have not only a technical dimension, “because it covers economic, social, political and national security issues”.
These questions, he said, “requires the work of the entire system of State economic administration, which includes a group of authorities which the Constitution unites in the executive branch of the State”.
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world had already completed the transition to digital broadcasting, and had done so with the help of the executive, despite the existence of highly specialized technical institutions.
It cannot be concluded from this that the Government, by adopting the decree under discussion, which in any case affects the competence of Congress, ensures administrative compliance with the laws adopted by the Legislative Assembly, he said.
Michoacán is analyzing the possibility of counting voice by voice.
According to the EDP, the difference between the first and second seats in the Governor ' s elections is only 27 per cent, even without counting the votes of 879 out of the total of 6.074 minutes.
The possibility of counting “voting by vote” is real with regard to this year's electoral process in Michoacán, where, according to the Provisional Electoral Results Programme (PRRP), the difference between the first and second seats in the governor's elections is only 27 per cent, even without counting the 879 votes in the total of 6.074 minutes.
In the light of this, the President of the General Council of the Michoacán Electoral Institute (MIE), Maria de Los Angeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, on 9 November, the electorate had adopted a set of principles to harmonize local rules with federal electoral reform.
It should be recalled that Michoacán did not adopt the State Constitution or Electoral Code or the Electoral Law, as the State Congress approved the reforms shortly before the legal date for their entry into force in the electoral process and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel did not include its publication within the time limits set by the law in the State Official Gazette, stating that he had some objections.
On the same day, 9 November, the Supreme Court of Justice (JJJJ) decided on a constitutional claim filed by the local legislature and called the state's constitutional reform representative's “invalid and illegal” voice, as it had no right to “authorize or support them”.
In an interview on the possibility of a “vote for vote”, Maria de los Angeles Llanderal argued that, with the adoption of suitable principles, it would be possible for the IMS General Council to submit a partial or complete vote count to the local electoral body.
Thus, a partial recalculation of one or more ballot boxes may be made under the conditions that: the results of the minutes do not coincide; there is no record of voting and counting in the ballot box or is not available to the President; or there are obvious errors or corrections in the record.
In addition, there may be a general recount of votes in all ballot boxes when there is an indication that the difference between the expected winner of the election under consideration and the second ballot is less than or equal to one per cent, provided that there is a request at the beginning of the session from a representative of the party and/or coalition that has nominated the second candidate.
A general recount will also be made if, at the end of the normal count, it is established that the difference between the winner and the candidate in second place is less than or equal to 1 per cent, provided that there is a petition from the political party whose candidate is second, in the event that the ballot boxes that were counted in part are excluded.
It is worth noting that this is the case for the elections in Morelia, where, according to EDP, the difference between first and second place is only 0.16%, even excluding 129 votes out of a total of 923 protocol.
