The Prime Minister-designate, Mario Monti, will meet tomorrow with the President of Italy to present a new Government that will face a crisis that has brought this country to the brink of economic disaster.
The appointed Italian Prime Minister, Mario Monti, will meet with the Italian President on Wednesday to present a new government that will face a crisis that has brought Italy to the brink of economic disaster and has damaged the entire eurozone.
A statement from the presidential palace stated that Monty, appointed on Sunday, would meet with the President, Giorgio Napolitano, on Wednesday to confirm that he could form a government.
He was expected to present a cabinet composed mainly of technocrats, although it was not clear when the new executive would take up its position.
Monty said that he would present to the President the results of his negotiations with the political parties in his attempt to form a Government.
“I want to reaffirm my full confidence in our country's ability to get out of this difficult period,” the former European Commissioner said to reporters.
Monty did not make it clear that he was able to form a government, but the tone of his comments showed that the obstacles had been overcome.
"The structure is now well-defined," he said.
Monty completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, much less the usual, as Italy was struggling with the political and financial crisis that put their debt at a critical level.
The administration, under the leadership of former European Commissioner Monty, must approve the austerity package required by European leaders in order to restore confidence in Italy.
