Ex-President Alberto Fujimori was hospitalized on Tuesday at a public hospital, and his family doctor informed him about the loss of muscle force in his legs.
Fujimori, 72 years of age, who has been sentenced to 25 years in prison for human rights violations committed during his reign (1990-2000), suffers from several diseases, including language cancer, which has led to his surgery four times and is being monitored.
Congressman Alejandro Aginaga, who is his personal doctor, told television channel N that Fujimori would be examined in three days at the National Institute of Neoplastic Diseases to determine the cause of pain and loss of strength in his lower limbs.
Aginaga said that, in his view, Fujimori should be a candidate for the benefit of a pardon for humanitarian reasons; however, he said that he did not want it because he knew he was innocent.
He's had four operations on the cancer of his tongue, and he's lost 18 kilos in weight, plus other diseases, such as severe erosive gastroitis, pancreatic cysts, kidney stones, high blood pressure, and blood circulation problems in his legs, listed by the doctor.
Fujimori has been in prison since September 2007, at the National Special Operations Police Department.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the murder of 25 persons by the army destruction squad, which operated in secret during the early years of his rule.
Mojica is going to Mexico to strengthen political ties.
An official delegation led by the President of Uruguay, José Muhika, and composed of several ministers and businessmen, will come to Mexico this Tuesday to expand trade between the two countries and to begin negotiations on the political problems of the region.
The Muhika will meet next Wednesday with his Mexican colleague, Felipe Calderón, the most important item in the extensive plan to meet with the political, commercial and community of Uruguayans living in Mexico, in accordance with the timetable published by the Uruguayan leadership.
The meeting of the two Presidents in Guadalajara will be “favourable for the exchange of information on political relations between the two nations”, as the South American leadership published on its website.
According to local media, Muhika is seeking Calderón's support for Uruguay in an incident with France when French President Nicolas Sarkozy listed a South American country as a tax haven at a meeting of the G20 in the French city of Cannes.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened to exclude from the international community those countries that remained tax havens, a statement that provoked Uruguay's protest and the withdrawal for consultations of his Ambassador to the European country.
Mexico has chaired the G20 since November, a group formed from the most developed and developing countries, and has, in fact, had with the South American country since January this year an agreement on the exchange of tax information to avoid double taxation.
The Government of Uruguay has tried in recent years to expedite the conclusion of tax exchange agreements in order to withdraw from the grey list of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development, drawn from countries that do not use international standards for tax cooperation.
With regard to the trade plan, Mexico and Uruguay had been in force since 2004 with the Free Trade Agreement (FTA), which had increased trade between the two countries.
The mustache plumber will be 3D with "Super Mario 3D Land"
Super Mario fought tirelessly for over 25 years to save Princess Peach from Bowser's evil paws, but he's never done it in three dimensions before: at Super Mario 3D Land, he's gonna fight for a girl's love in stereoscopic technology.
The publication, which will appear in shops around the world this month, is based on the characteristics of the Nintendo 3DS portable console, which allows three dimensions to be played without the use of glasses.
"Mario is a hero who has to tell you how the stereos are going to work without glasses," said the chief of the press office of Nintendo in Spain, Omar Álvarez, when he presented the game in Madrid.
Alvarez said that "Super Mario 3D Land" is "Nintendo's first video game specially designed for this platform," because until now successful products like "Star Fox 64 3D" or "Zelda: Ocarina of Time 3D" have adapted existing games.
The representative of Nintendo said that, despite the existence of the 3D, Super Mario 3D Land was a "accessible" video game that allowed for the enjoyment of a fast and mobile game.
Alvarez said that "Super Mario 3D Land" contains two games in one: the first part "simple" to attract less experienced users.
One day, most experts will go "second round" to levels of the game, which this time are more complex.
In addition, users may choose in real time between "D aggressive" or one that affects only the depth of the action, but which needs to be played in three dimensions in order to overcome a variety of obstacles and "do not succumb to optical illusions".
This invasion of Super Mario into three dimensions also marks the return of the hero to the portable console, which has not happened since 2005.
In this game, Nintendo winks at the fans of the series and repeats a successful formula from previous games, a plumber with a mustache needs to go through dangerously mined platforms to free Princess Peach.
However, the player will discover new movements, decorations, costumes, and enemies, as well as "player" Luigi.
Colom guarantees Portillo's extradition to the United States
President Alvaro Colom said on Tuesday that the extradition process of Alfonso Portillo had begun so that he would answer in the United States for the conspiracy to launder $70 million.
This is the end of the process by which Guatemala responded to a request from a northern country that requested Portillo to be extradited to try him there.
At a press conference, Colom said that his decision was linked to the independence of the judiciary and the executive, given that the court of first instance had already signed the extradition.
He claimed that, during his mandate, he had not “handled” legal decisions and had taken all extradition procedures of which he had ever been aware.
Together with Portillo Sergio Ruano Marroquín, he will be extradited for murder and grievous bodily harm, as well as Edgar Estrada Morales and Victor Estrada Paredes, both for drug trafficking.
What Colom has done shows the executive process after all the legal and constitutional courts have been exhausted to prosecute the former Head of State from 2000 to 2004.
In accordance with the decisions of the Fifth Criminal Court and the Constitutional Court, Portillo will be extradited once, with a ruling on his legal situation in Guatemala and the guarantee of his human rights.
Portillo was found innocent of the embezzlement of Q120 million in the Ministry of Defence during the presidential term, which was a pre-extradition process, but the Ministry of Public Relations appealed and reopened the case.
