Minister Dionysio Pérez Hacome describes the details of the disaster that killed the Minister of the Interior, Francisco Blake, and seven others.
The Minister of Communications and Transport (MST) reported that results obtained in an accident in which the Minister of the Interior, Francisco Blake Maura, and seven others were killed, showed that the helicopter had hit the ground directly in complete integrity, without the pilot attempting to make an emergency landing.
During a press conference, Dionysio Pérez Hacome, Minister of Communications and Transport, said that before the aircraft went up, the pilot had discovered that the weather conditions were suitable for flight.
"Elements that seem to indicate that the ship had several contacts with the ground, wings came into contact with trees 25 meters away, where the vehicle lost its fluselage."
He also stated that the vessel was intended for 19 persons, respectively, and that it met the necessary requirements for the transport of persons.
He also said that studies conducted in the area of impact did not report the presence of parts on the ground.
“The study states that there are no components of the vessel elsewhere, and the impact occurred in a state of structural integrity.
"The helicopter was intended for 19 passengers, which met the relevant requirements for the transport of passengers.
The ground in this place has a seven to 30 degree slope.
At this point, the secretary said, the most important thing is to get the results as soon as possible; however, the study may take months or even a year.
Meanwhile, Gilberto López Meyer, Director General of Airports and Support Services, said that during the strike, a presidential helicopter was operating at cruise speed and that it happened on soft rising soil.
"This information reinforces the hypothesis of a normal flight manoeuvre at the moment of impact," he said.
At a press conference, the owner of SCT, Perez Hacome, listed six important elements in the investigation:
Visual flight:
According to aviation regulations, the flight was conducted according to visual flight rules, which means that the crew must have visibility during flight and landing.
Weather conditions:
The AICM reports identified suitable conditions for taking off when the aircraft headed towards the border area between Mexico City and the Mexican State, where clouds were seen at low altitudes.
Selected routes:
It is possible that because of cloud conditions, the team was searching for a lower altitude and greater visibility in the Quernawak Valley.
Place of impact.
The coordinates of the impact and the last recording from the aircraft radar probably did not lose control or change direction before the impact.
Fragmentation of debris in a small area:
The information available so far indicates that the impact was on the front and side lines.
The dispersion of the debris suggests that the helicopter encountered the ground under structural conditions.
There were no obvious signs of fire or explosion:
Undetected evidence in the wreckage of the ship, some kind of explosion or fire remains in the disaster zone.
Recent research shows that there may have been multiple contacts with the land.
During the work on the site, pieces of aircraft were found at an altitude of 9,200 feet above sea level, and the ground ranges from 7 degrees to 30 degrees.
The pictures show the sequence in which it was destroyed along the way.
The information contains facts that seem to indicate that the helicopter may have had several clashes with the ground.
After careful research, no scattered parts of the aircraft were found in larger areas than the defined area near the site of the disaster, thus reinforcing the assumption that the impact occurred under structural integrity.
MSS announces an obese gene search program
Social protection leads research on finding obesity gene in children and young people, supported by IPN experts
The Mexican Institute of Social Protection (MSSI) announced that it was conducting a study to detect the gene of obesity in children and young people, known as the protocol “Genetics of obesity in childhood and adolescence”, which would provide a count of overweight.
In his statement, Miguel Cruz López, Head of the Biochemistry Research Unit of the National Centre for Medicine of the Twenty-first Century, explained that a multidisciplinary team of physicians, nurses, dietologists and social workers had been assembled.
This team is assisted by specialists and postgraduate students from the National Health Institute (NIPH) and the Centre for Scientific Research and Higher Education (CINVESTAV) of the National Polytechnic Institute (NPI).
The study invites the public (prescribed or not) to participate in the MSSI sports centres participating in the study in Mexico Valley, where children will be tested every Saturday morning at 8:00 a.m.
He stressed that the protocol had been launched at a sports centre in Cuautemoke (in western Mexico state) and that since 8 October, events had been held at a sports centre in Nesaualcoyotl (East Mexico state).
Once the goal of 500 to 600 children has been achieved, the study will continue at the Independence Sports Centre (South Mexico City) and finally at the Morelos Sports Centre (north Mexico City).
He explained that the aim of the study was to understand the ingredients and importance of genetics for the development of obesity and to establish a risk factor among children and young Mexicans in order to prevent the emergence of chronic degenerative diseases.
World Diabetes Day will be observed on 14 November, with the main objective of collecting 3,000 children and adolescents between the ages of 6 and 14, with parental permission and supervision, to complete individual nutrition questionnaires.
They will also be asked about physical activity and the history of family inherited diseases in order to avoid risk factors that lead to diseases such as diabetes or renal failure.
He explained that an anthropometric measurement of all participants (weight, height and waist covering), blood pressure and glucose, fat, cholesterol and insulin, and genetic analysis (to identify genes associated with childhood obesity) would be conducted on Saturday.
Cruz Lopez said that the study reflected the concern of health professionals about the alarming increase in child weight.
Medical studies carried out between 1999 and 2006 show that there has been an increase in just six years: 77 per cent of boys were obese, 47 per cent of girls; overweight also showed a significant increase,” said MSSI.
He said that the rationale for finding markers was based on the fact that the population was different from other peoples in its genetic history.
He reported that, on average, Mexican was 65 per cent American Indian, 30 per cent European and 5 per cent African, a condition that affected genes associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that the main effect of the genetics of obesity is the body's inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calories) and it's stored as fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit to participants was a comprehensive assessment of children, which could determine whether they had any excess weight or obesity.
Even, he said, the presence of dark folds on the neck (acant) and forearms means the possibility of metabolism being violated and even prediabetes.
The information is treated with confidentiality, and the doctors give it in writing to the parents, to whom they explain all the measurements and changes in lifestyle that must be made in order to avoid the disease.
Cruz Lopez explained that there were three main reasons for overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: sitting life, or lack of daily physical activity, spending most of the day at home in front of television, and using transportation at short distances instead of walking.
This is also due to the high consumption of calories, i.e., increased consumption of sweet drinks and carbohydrates (talamel, bread, pizzas, hamburgers, etc.) with high fat and protein content and the genetic predisposition analysed in the programme.
UNAM asphalt can avoid cracks
Raphael Herrera, a researcher at the UNAM Chemical Faculty, developed a polymer-modified bitumen to produce a mixture of best quality, resistant to environmental and temperature effects.
If attention had been paid to the signals sent by the road surface, it would have been necessary to repair about 200,000 pits per rainy season in the metropolitan area of Mexico City, says Rafael Herrera Nahera, researcher at the UNAM Faculty of Chemistry, and adds that if the construction and maintenance of the paved road surface is correct, the number of pits can be reduced or even reduced to zero.
In his lecture, The Technology View of the Pits of the International Year of Chemistry reports that the laboratory for which he is responsible develops a polymer-modified bitumen to produce a mixture with characteristics close to the bitumen but with better resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nahera said that this type of modified bitumen could be used in places where the weather was extremely hot, as in some cities in the north, to improve the quality of roads and, consequently, to counteract pit formation.
He explained that the bitumen, the heavier part of the oil, was the sequence of hydrocarbon molecules, some high molecular mass, called asphalts, and others low molecular mass, called Maltens, which together gave the road surface its characteristic viscous behaviour.
The viscous behavior of the bitumen is the fact that at high temperatures it behaves like a liquid at 120, and at 50 degrees Celsius it maintains a near solid state, while at very low temperatures the bitumen becomes fragile, he said.
This means that the resistance to street asphalt is not constant, but changes during the day, depending on natural conditions and temperature, has been said by a chemical engineer.
The scientist observed that the streets of Mexico City were mostly covered with flexible coatings made up of six layers of material, of which the last three included bitumen.
Among the uppermost layers is bitumen made of small stones, dropped into bitumen and then compressed.
Every stone that makes this coating, he said, is in bitumen.
When driving and working, this helps the force to spread very well over the road surface.
If it were modified asphalt, they would be distributed even better, said the chemical engineer.
On the asphalt surface, he added, there was a last layer called a layer of wear, which was made of a small stone, actually sand, also submerged in the asphalt.
Since it is a layer that will be in contact with the wheels of transport, it should have more resistance than the asphalt surface and allow for road friction.
As part of the road surface that will receive and disseminate these forces, the wear layer also requires an appropriate thickness and the material from which it is made must be taken into account.
Weather, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also very important factors for consideration, especially water, he said, because it significantly affects the state of the asphalt.
When the ground is wet, the water penetrates the surface and it's hard for it to get out of it, it softens all the layers of the surface, and hence the formation of pits.
When the pits are formed, he said, the wear layer is first worn out, and only then does it affect the bitumen, but the damage does not occur instantaneously, a process that should be taken into account at the first indicators of maintenance programmes.
A member of the National Research System also explained that transport is another important factor in the formation of holes, and therefore the thickness of each surface layer must always be linked to the transport load and this requirement must be guaranteed in order to prevent the frequent occurrence of pits.
Rafael Herrera said that relatively bitumen still has a lot to study and do, for example, bitumen emulsions, which in other countries are already on the market and even help to fix pits with ease and without high temperatures.
