The “gold rule” budget in the Constitution
The leadership of the great coalition of Social Democrats and Christian Democrats in power in Austria decided on Tuesday to put the budget “gold rule” in the constitution to reduce the budget deficit and thus avoid possible downgrading of Austria's public credit rating (triple A) by rating agencies.
The Chancellor of Social Democrat Werner Faymann himself announced this decision at the end of a meeting of the Council of Ministers, with an Austrian public debt of 74.6 per cent, significantly higher than the 60 per cent threshold set by the Maastricht Treaty, but lower than the public debt of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
If Austria’s solvency had fallen by only one point, from AAA to AA+, we would have to pay three thousand million euros more each year, the argument of Vice Chancellor and Foreign Minister Michael Spindelegger of Christian Democrats.
Austria is thus implementing the Euro-zone summit on 26 October in Brussels; the heads of State and Government demanded a reduction in fiscal deficits by the end of 2012 and a return to balanced government accounts through a constitution or equivalent law.
The Austrian Government's regulation resembles the “German model”, since Germany was the first European country to adopt this “rule”.
Until 2017, the structural deficit of the State budget must be reduced by 0.75% of gross domestic product (GDP) each year, and from 2017 the structural deficit of the State budget of the federal State must not exceed 0.35% of GDP in any year, and the land, like the communes, must present balanced budgets.
The goal is to bring public debt below the 60 per cent target set by the Maastricht Treaty by 2020/2021.
