Is immigration a burden or a benefit to the economy?
The immigration policy of Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized on various sides - the overloading of police, judicial and administrative services subordinated to the policy of numbers and the compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of France as a “State of human rights”.
Then there was the administrative harassment of foreign students, which came into the news when the Home Secretary (“Liberación” of 23 May) stated that France “does not need foreign talents, masons and waiters”.
But it is rarely analysed from an economic point of view.
There is much agreement between the right and left.
On the right hand, Jacques Chirac stated in 1976 that “900,000 unemployed will not be a problem in a country with 2 million foreign workers” and on the left by Michel Rocar, who explained in 1990 that France “can't accept the world's poor”.
The only difference is in the level of generosity.
In 2005, fear of intrusion into the country by a Polish plumber was felt by both left and right.
Both sides see immigration as a burden for the French economy and for French society.
The only difference is the level of generosity that they would be willing to show to immigrants.
In his programme, François Hollande confined himself to platitudes, saying that “joint work will solve our immigration problem”.
This perception of immigration as a burden and a problem may offer an electoral advantage, but it is economically costly.
As the economists Ian Goldin and Jeffrey Cameron remind us in a recent book summarizing recent immigration data (Special People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Publishing, 352 pages), there is a broad consensus among professionals on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and employment in countries that accept immigrants.
Restriction of immigration weakens growth and reduces employment.
The fear of the influence of immigrants is based on the notion that they can replace local workers, especially the low-skilled, by triggering wage declines.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are much more complementary than replacing local labour with jobs that lack local labour.
Unskilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract local labour and the most skilled in dynamic sectors where training is not linked to job offers.
Positive impact on wages
Just as it would be difficult for a surgeon to work in a country where there is a shortage of anaesthetists, the complementarity that exists between local and immigrant workers has led to a positive impact on the wages of local workers.
Giovanni Peri calculated that a 1 per cent increase in migration flows resulted in an increase of 0.6 to 0.9 per cent in real long-term wages.
This is without taking into account the fact that the diversity of immigrants contributes to the creation of new ideas and economic growth (a large proportion of the Nobel laureates in America are naturalized immigrants, while Google, Intel, Paypal and Yahoo were all founded by immigrants).
Migrants also make a net profit in social security systems, accounting for an average of 1% of total European budgets.
The World Labour Organization estimates that, for example, in Germany, an immigrant who arrives at the age of 30 years will earn a net income (income minus expenditure) to the State budget on average of 150,000 euros.
Nicolas Sarkozy, at the beginning of his mandate, was about to take on the missing growth points.
These teeth, which were used to deter immigrants, had the exact opposite effect.
