Why is the unemployment rate among disabled workers so high?
Approximately 19 per cent of persons with disabilities seek work.
The 15th week of employment for persons with disabilities begins today.
Despite the public charity policy launched in 2005, the unemployment rate for persons with disabilities is still twice as high as the average, i.e. 19 per cent, compared with 9 per cent for the general population.
Disappointing?
"No," stresses Eric Blanche, CEO of Adapt, an organization that organizes a week of employment for the disabled."
"In 15 years, significant progress has been made."
"At that time, the unemployment rate was three times higher than two."
"However, there's still a lot of work to be done."
It must be said that there are still many obstacles to employment for a disabled person.
Of these, 37 per cent are older than 50 (17 per cent on average).
They are more likely to have low qualifications: 80 per cent do not have a bachelor ' s degree, and of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very widespread, at 85 per cent for persons with disabilities, compared with 38 per cent on average.
In short, these are all criteria that make it very difficult to return to work and which are the essence of the problem”, according to Christian Grapin, Director General Tremplin, an association established in 1992 to help companies hire a disabled worker.
Here are some of the obstacles.
There's no need to talk about a mentality that's changing, but it's too slow.
A study carried out in April by IMS-Entreprendre for Cité showed that the managers interviewed had a low level of knowledge of disability and “perceived people in wheelchairs or with mental or mental disabilities”.
The result is that private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from the target of 6 per cent of disabled workers set in the 1987 law.
The last known figures for 2008 are 2.6 per cent.
"Today we're about 3%," says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiff, an organization responsible for collecting tax from companies that do not comply with this law.
Evidence: The number of “taxable” organizations decreased from 59,000 to 46,000 in 2007-2011 (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which raised the tax, put a lot of pressure on the companies," explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects a growing awareness, particularly in large enterprises."
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59 per cent of organizations with 20 to 49 employees have disabled workers, compared with 82 per cent with 100 to 199 employees.
